    "id": "slide3",
    "eyebrow": "Historical Period",
    "num": "03",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">03</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Historical Period</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">The Mexican Texas Era: 1820-1836</h2><ul><li>Texican identity is rooted in the Mexican Texas period</li><li>This era spans from Mexican independence to the Texas Revolution</li><li>Texicans lived under Mexican law and governance</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans were Mexican citizens residing in Texas during the period when Texas was part of Mexico. This era ended with the Texas Revolution in 1836, after which the political landscape changed dramatically. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> In 1835, a Texican landowner in Gonzales would have been subject to Mexican laws and taxes, unlike Anglo settlers pushing for independence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how political changes during 1820-1836 affected Texican identity and loyalties.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the significance of Mexican governance in shaping Texican culture and political stance.</p></div></div>",
