      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans were Mexican citizens residing in Texas during the period when Texas was part of Mexico. This era ended with the Texas Revolution in 1836, after which the political landscape changed dramatically.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texican identity is rooted in the Mexican Texas period</li><li>This era spans from Mexican independence to the Texas Revolution</li><li>Texicans lived under Mexican law and governance</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>In 1835, a Texican landowner in Gonzales would have been subject to Mexican laws and taxes, unlike Anglo settlers pushing for independence.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Consider how political changes during 1820-1836 affected Texican identity and loyalties.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Overlooking the significance of Mexican governance in shaping Texican culture and political stance.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
