    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">07</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Historical Context</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Origins of the Term 'Texas' and Indigenous Influence</h2><ul><li>'Texas' derives from the Caddo word 'táysha' meaning 'friends' or 'allies'</li><li>Indigenous peoples shaped early regional identity</li><li>Texican identity includes indigenous cultural influences</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The name 'Texas' itself reflects indigenous origins, underscoring the deep-rooted cultural influences that shaped Texican identity beyond Hispanic and Anglo elements. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The Caddo confederacy's use of 'táysha' influenced Spanish and Mexican naming conventions for the region.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how indigenous heritage contributes to Texican identity.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking indigenous contributions when focusing solely on Hispanic or Anglo narratives.</p></div></div>",
