      "secnum": "Deep Dive 16",
      "h": "Language and Religion in Texican Identity Formation",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Language and religion were key markers distinguishing Texicans from Anglo settlers. Spanish and Catholicism reinforced Texican cultural identity, while Anglo settlers' English and Protestantism introduced new cultural elements, contributing to social tensions.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Spanish was the primary language of Texicans</li><li>Catholicism was central to Texican community life</li><li>Anglo settlers introduced English and Protestantism</li><li>Religious and linguistic differences heightened social divides</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican churches served as community centers preserving Mexican traditions amid Anglo Protestant influences.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss how language and religion shaped Texican social identity.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring the role of religion and language in cultural conflicts.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p>"
