    "eyebrow": "Social Hierarchy",
    "num": "17",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">17</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Social Hierarchy</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Social Structure and Community Roles</h2><ul><li>Texican society was organized around family and landownership</li><li>Ranching elites held significant social and political power</li><li>Community cohesion was maintained through kinship and religion</li><li>Social roles adapted to frontier challenges and alliances</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican social structure centered on extended families and landowning ranchers who dominated local politics. Kinship ties and Catholic faith reinforced community bonds, while frontier conditions required flexible social roles. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Prominent Texican ranching families often led local militias and political councils.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify key social roles within Texican communities and their functions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming a rigid social hierarchy without recognizing frontier adaptability.</p></div><div id=\"quiz-slide29\" class=\"quizbox popquiz anim\" data-quiz=\"[{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;mc&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:2,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Which of the following best defines the term &#39;Texican&#39; during the period of Mexican Texas (1820-1836)?&quot;,&quot;options&quot;:[&quot;An Anglo-American settler who moved to Texas after 1836&quot;,&quot;A Mexican citizen living in Texas before the Texas Revolution&quot;,&quot;A Native American tribe in Texas&quot;,&quot;A Spanish explorer who founded Texas&quot;],&quot;answer&quot;:1,&quot;why&quot;:&quot;The term &#39;Texican&#39; refers to Mexican citizens residing in Texas during Mexican Texas before the Texas Revolution, distinguishing them from Anglo settlers and indigenous peoples.&quot;},{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;sa&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:3,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Explain the role of the Texicans in early Texas history and how their cultural identity differed from both Mexicans in Mexico and later Anglo-American settlers.&quot;,&quot;rubric&quot;:&quot;Response should include discussion of Texicans&#39; political affiliations during Mexican Texas, their participation in the Texas Revolution, and their unique cultural identity blending Mexican heritage with frontier conditions. It should also note distinctions from Mexicans in Mexico and Anglo settlers arriving later.&quot;,&quot;sample&quot;:&quot;Texicans were Mexican citizens living in Texas who played a key role in early Texas history, including involvement in the Texas Revolution. Their cultural identity was distinct because they combined Mexican traditions with frontier lifestyle adaptations, differing from Mexicans in Mexico and Anglo settlers who arrived after 1836.&quot;,&quot;accept&quot;:[&quot;Texicans were Mexican residents of Texas who contributed politically and militarily to early Texas history, especially the Texas Revolution. They had a unique cultural identity blending Mexican roots and frontier life, distinct from Mexicans in Mexico and later Anglo settlers.&quot;,&quot;The Texicans were Mexican citizens living in Texas before independence, involved in the revolution and culturally different from both Mexicans in Mexico and Anglo settlers due to their frontier experiences.&quot;]}]\" data-pop=\"1\"></div></div>",
