      "secnum": "Deep Dive 17",
      "h": "Texican Social Organization on the Frontier",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican social structure centered on extended families and landowning ranchers who dominated local politics. Kinship ties and Catholic faith reinforced community bonds, while frontier conditions required flexible social roles.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; shsulibraryguides.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texican society was organized around family and landownership</li><li>Ranching elites held significant social and political power</li><li>Community cohesion was maintained through kinship and religion</li><li>Social roles adapted to frontier challenges and alliances</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Prominent Texican ranching families often led local militias and political councils.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify key social roles within Texican communities and their functions.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming a rigid social hierarchy without recognizing frontier adaptability.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; shsulibraryguides.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p>"
