    "id": "slide30",
    "eyebrow": "Political Identity",
    "num": "18",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">18</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Political Identity</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Political Affiliations and Loyalties</h2><ul><li>Texicans initially supported Mexican federalism over centralism</li><li>Many opposed Santa Anna’s centralist policies</li><li>Political loyalties split during the Texas Revolution</li><li>Texicans sought to protect local autonomy and cultural rights</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican political identity was shaped by support for Mexican federalism and opposition to centralist policies under Santa Anna. This political stance influenced their divided loyalties during the Texas Revolution, balancing cultural preservation with political change. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican leaders petitioned Mexican authorities for greater local control before supporting independence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explain how Texican political views influenced their role in the revolution.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Viewing Texicans as uniformly pro-independence without recognizing federalist loyalties.</p></div><div id=\"quiz-slide30\" class=\"quizbox popquiz anim\" data-quiz=\"[{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;mc&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:2,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Which of the following best defines the term &#39;Texican&#39; during the period of Mexican Texas (1820-1836)?&quot;,&quot;options&quot;:[&quot;An Anglo-American settler who moved to Texas after 1836&quot;,&quot;A Mexican citizen living in Texas before the Texas Revolution&quot;,&quot;A Native American tribe in Texas&quot;,&quot;A Spanish explorer who founded Texas&quot;],&quot;answer&quot;:1,&quot;why&quot;:&quot;The term &#39;Texican&#39; refers to Mexican citizens residing in Texas during Mexican Texas before the Texas Revolution, distinguishing them from Anglo settlers and indigenous peoples.&quot;},{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;sa&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:3,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Explain the role of the Texicans in early Texas history and how their cultural identity differed from both Mexicans in Mexico and later Anglo-American settlers.&quot;,&quot;rubric&quot;:&quot;Response should include discussion of Texicans&#39; political affiliations during Mexican Texas, their participation in the Texas Revolution, and their unique cultural identity blending Mexican heritage with frontier conditions. It should also note distinctions from Mexicans in Mexico and Anglo settlers arriving later.&quot;,&quot;sample&quot;:&quot;Texicans were Mexican citizens living in Texas who played a key role in early Texas history, including involvement in the Texas Revolution. Their cultural identity was distinct because they combined Mexican traditions with frontier lifestyle adaptations, differing from Mexicans in Mexico and Anglo settlers who arrived after 1836.&quot;,&quot;accept&quot;:[&quot;Texicans were Mexican residents of Texas who contributed politically and militarily to early Texas history, especially the Texas Revolution. They had a unique cultural identity blending Mexican roots and frontier life, distinct from Mexicans in Mexico and later Anglo settlers.&quot;,&quot;The Texicans were Mexican citizens living in Texas before independence, involved in the revolution and culturally different from both Mexicans in Mexico and Anglo settlers due to their frontier experiences.&quot;]}]\" data-pop=\"1\"></div></div>",
