      "secnum": "Deep Dive 18",
      "h": "Texican Political Loyalties in a Divided Landscape",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican political identity was shaped by support for Mexican federalism and opposition to centralist policies under Santa Anna. This political stance influenced their divided loyalties during the Texas Revolution, balancing cultural preservation with political change.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans initially supported Mexican federalism over centralism</li><li>Many opposed Santa Anna’s centralist policies</li><li>Political loyalties split during the Texas Revolution</li><li>Texicans sought to protect local autonomy and cultural rights</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican leaders petitioned Mexican authorities for greater local control before supporting independence.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Explain how Texican political views influenced their role in the revolution.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Viewing Texicans as uniformly pro-independence without recognizing federalist loyalties.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p>"
