      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This quiz assesses learners’ comprehension of the cultural and political distinctions among Texicans, Mexicans, and Anglo settlers, reinforcing key concepts from this section.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com; legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu; shsulibraryguides.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Multiple choice questions on cultural and political distinctions</li><li>Identify correct statements about Texican identity</li><li>Test understanding of social tensions and loyalties</li><li>Immediate feedback to reinforce learning</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Question: Which group primarily spoke Spanish and practiced Catholicism? Answer: Texicans and Mexicans.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Complete the quiz and review explanations for each answer.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Confusing Texicans with Anglo settlers in cultural traits.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com; legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu; shsulibraryguides.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p>"
